'''''Collybia tuberosa''''', commonly known as the '''lentil shanklet''' or the '''appleseed coincap''', is an inedible [[species]] of [[fungus]] in the [[Tricholomataceae]] family, and the [[type species]] of the genus ''[[Collybia]]''. Like the two other members of its genus, it lives on the decomposing remains of other fleshy [[mushroom]]s. The fungus produces small whitish [[basidiocarp|fruit bodies]] with [[pileus (mycology)|caps]] up to {{convert|1|cm|in|1|abbr=on}} wide held by thin [[stipe (mycology)|stems]] up to {{convert|5|cm|in|1|abbr=on}} long. On the underside of the cap are closely spaced white [[lamella (mycology)|gills]] that are broadly attached to the stem. At the base of the stem, embedded in the [[substrate (biology)|substrate]] is a small reddish-brown [[sclerotium]] that somewhat resembles an apple seed. The appearance of the sclerotium distinguishes it from the other two species of ''Collybia'', which are otherwise very similar in overall appearance. ''C.&nbsp;tuberosa'' is found in Europe, North America, and Japan, growing in dense clusters on species of ''[[Lactarius]]'' and ''[[Russula]]'', [[bolete]]s, [[hydnum]]s, and [[polypore]]s.

==Taxonomy, phylogeny, and naming==

