| caption=Phylogeny and relationships of ''C.&nbsp;tuberosa'' and closely related fungi based on [[ribosomal DNA]] sequences.<ref name=Hughes2001/>
}}

The species was first described under the name ''Agaricus tuberosus'' by the French naturalist [[Jean Baptiste Fran<U+00E7>ois Pierre Bulliard|Jean Bulliard]] in the 6th volume of his ''Herbier de la France'' (1786).<ref name=Bulliard1786/> [[Christian Hendrik Persoon]] called it ''Agaricus amanitae'' [[subspecies|subsp.]] ''tuberosus'' in his 1799 publication ''Observationes Mycologicae'',<ref name=Persoon1799/> while [[Samuel Frederick Gray]] referred it to ''[[Gymnopus]]'' in 1821.<ref name=Gray1821/> It was transferred to ''[[Collybia]]'' by [[Paul Kummer]] in 1886.<ref name=Kummer1871/> The species has also been called ''Microcollybia tuberata'' in a 1979 publication by Joanne Lennox,<ref name=Lennox1979/> but the genus ''Microcollybia'' has since been folded into ''Collybia''.<ref name=Kirk2008/> Additional [[synonym (taxonomy)|taxonomic synonyms]] include ''Marasmius sclerotipes'' Bres. 1881, ''Chamaeceras sclerotipes'' (Bres.) Kuntze 1898, and ''Collybia sclerotipes'' (Bres.) S.Ito 1950.<ref name="urlMycoBank: Collybia tuberosa"/>

[[Molecular phylogenetics|Molecular phylogenetic]] analysis reported in 2001 used [[RNA sequence]]s to establish that ''C.&nbsp;tuberosa'' forms a [[monophyletic]] group with ''[[Collybia cookei|C.&nbsp;cookei]]'' and ''[[Collybia cirrhata|C.&nbsp;cirrhata]]'';<ref name=Hughes2001/> this finding was later corroborated in a 2006 publication.<ref name=Machnicki2006/>

The [[specific epithet]] ''tuberosa'' is derived from the [[Latin]] word for "tuberous".<ref name=Runkel2009/> The mushroom is [[common name|commonly]] known as the "lentil shanklet",<ref name="urlRogers"/> or the "appleseed coincap".<ref name=McKnight1987/> Samuel Gray called it the "tuberous naked-foot" in his 1821 ''Natural Arrangement of British plants''.<ref name=Gray1821/>

==Description==
[[image:Collybia tuberosa Bulliard-.jpg|thumb|left|Bulliard's original drawing of ''C.&nbsp;tuberosa'']]
The [[pileus (mycology)|cap]] of ''C.&nbsp;tuberosa'' ranges in shape from obtusely convex to cushion-shaped with a margin curved inward when young, to flattened in age, with margin curved downward to straight. The cap sometimes has a shallow depression in the center,<ref name="urlHalling"/> or a shallow [[umbo (mycology)|umbo]]. Its diameter is small, reaching a maximum of {{convert|10|mm|in|2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Phillips2005/> The cap surface is dry to moist, smooth to covered with fine soft hairs, and somewhat [[hygrophanous]]<U+2014>changing color depending on the level of hydration. Sometimes the cap margin is pleated or grooved. The center of the cap is pinkish-[[buff (color)|buff]] but whitish around the margin, and it becomes whitish overall as it matures. The [[trama (mycology)|flesh]] is thin, and colored whitish to light buff.<ref name="urlHalling"/> The mushroom has no distinctive taste or odor, and is considered inedible.<ref name=Phillips2005/>
[[image:Collybia.tuberosa2.-.lindsey.jpg|thumb|left|The white to buff-colored gills are bluntly attached to the stem and closely spaced.]]
The [[lamella (mycology)|gills]] are [[adnation|adnate]] (bluntly fused to the stem), becoming subdecurrent with age (running slightly down the length of the stem). The gill spacing is close to subdistant, and the individual gills are whitish to pinkish-buff, thin, narrow to moderately broad, and have straight edges. The [[stipe (mycology)|stem]] is {{convert|10|<U+2013>|50|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} long by {{convert|1|<U+2013>|2|mm|in|2|abbr=on}}, and roughly equal in width throughout its length. It is slender and thread-like, flexible and pliant, with a dry surface. The top of the stem is covered with scales or a fine whitish powder, while the lower portion has hairs ranging from delicate to coarse. The color of the stem is generally whitish to pinkish-buff, but it darkens after it has been handled. The stem interior is [[pith]]y, and becomes hollow with age. The stems originate from a dark reddish-brown [[sclerotium]] of variable shape, typically measuring {{convert|3|<U+2013>|12|mm|in|abbr=on}} by {{convert|2|<U+2013>|5|mm|in|2|abbr=on}}. The surface of the sclerotium is initially smooth, but later becomes wrinkled or furrowed; its interior is solid and white.<ref name="urlHalling"/> It is often compared to an apple seed in appearance.<ref name=McKnight1987/><ref name=Arora1986/> Typically, several sclerotia are connected by thin strands of [[mycelium|mycelia]].<ref name=McKnight1987/> The sclerotium is a resting structure that allows to fungus to overwinter in its host.<ref name="urlTom Volk's FTOM June 2004"/> In 1915, [[William Murrill]] reported the sclerotia of ''C.&nbsp;tuberosa'' to be [[bioluminescent]].<ref name=Murrill1915/>

The [[spore print]] is white.<ref name="urlKuo"/> Individual [[spore]]s are smooth, [[wikt:ellipsoid|ellipsoid]] to tear-shaped in profile, [[wikt:obovoid|obovoid]] to ellipsoid or cylindric in face or back view, with dimensions of 4.2<U+2013>6.2 by 2.8<U+2013>3.5[[micrometre|<U+00B5>m]]. They are [[amyloid (mycology)|inamyloid]] and [[wikt:acyanophilous|acyanophilous]] (non-reactive to [[staining]] with [[Melzer's reagent]] and [[Methyl blue]], respectively). The [[basidia]] (spore-bearing cells in the [[hymenium]]) are club-shaped to cylindric and 15.4<U+2013>21 by 3.5<U+2013>5&nbsp;<U+00B5>m. The cheilocystidia ([[cystidia]] on the gill edge) are scattered to infrequent, inconspicuous, and 17.5<U+2013>31.5&nbsp;<U+00B5>m long. Their shape ranges from a contorted cylinder to roughly club-shaped to irregularly diverticulate (with short offshoots approximately at right angles to the main stem). There are no pleurocystidia (cystidia on the gill face). The gill tissue is made of interwoven hyphae that are non-reactive to Melzer's reagent. These hyphae are smooth and thin-walled, measuring 2.8<U+2013>6.4&nbsp;<U+00B5>m in diameter. The cap tissue is made of hyphae that is interwoven below the center of the cap, radially oriented over the gills, and inamyloid. These hyphae are smooth, thin-walled, and 2.8<U+2013>7&nbsp;<U+00B5>m in diameter. The [[pileipellis|cap cuticle]] is a thin layer of smooth thin-walled hyphae that are more or less radially oriented, bent-over, cylindric and somewhat gelatinous, measuring 2<U+2013>5&nbsp;<U+00B5>m in diameter; they are occasionally diverticulate. The cuticle of the stem is made of a layer of parallel, vertically oriented smooth, thin-walled hyphae that are 2<U+2013>4.2&nbsp;<U+00B5>m in diameter, pale yellowish brown in alkali mounting solution. The stem has moderately thin-walled and smooth cystidia that are resemble [[wikt:flexuous|flexuous]] or contorted cylinders. They are [[hyaline]] in alkali, and 3.5<U+2013>7&nbsp;<U+00B5>m in diameter. [[Clamp connection]]s are present in the hyphae of all tissues.<ref name="urlHalling"/>

===Similar species===
{{multiple image
| footer = The lookalike species ''Baeospora myosura'' (right) and ''Strobilurus conigenoides'' (left) can be distinguished from ''C.&nbsp;tuberosa'' by their growth on cones.
| align = right
| image1 = Baeospora myosura 117706.jpg
| width1 = {{#expr: (150 * 1944 / 2592) round 0}}
| image2 = Strobilurus conigenoides 59060.jpg
| width2 = {{#expr: (150 * 3198 / 2470) round 0}}
}}
''[[Baeospora myosura]]'' is similar in size and appearance to ''C.&nbsp;tuberosa'', but grows on [[spruce]] and [[Douglas-fir]] cones.<ref name=Ammirati2009/> The "Magnolia coincap" (''[[Strobilurus conigenoides]]'') is smaller and grows on the cones of [[Magnolia]]s.<ref name=McKnight1987/> The two remaining ''Collybia'' species closely resemble ''C.&nbsp;tuberosa'', but can be distinguished by examining the stem bases at the point of attachment into the substrate. ''C.&nbsp;cookei'' has roughly spherical, light brown to yellowish sclerotia, while ''C.&nbsp;cirrhata'' does not produce sclerotia.<ref name="urlHalling"/> In the field, ''C.&nbsp;tuberosa'' may be distinguished from ''C.&nbsp;cookei'' by its dark reddish-brown sclerotia that somewhat resembles an appleseed.<ref name="urlKuo"/> A [[optical microscope|microscope]] provides a more definitive way of distinguishing the two: the hyphae in the sclerotia of ''C.&nbsp;cookei'' are rounded, while those of ''C.&nbsp;tuberosa'' are elongated; this diagnostic character is apparent with both fresh and dried material of the two species.<ref name=Komorowska2000/> In contrast, ''[[Collybia cirrhata|C.&nbsp;cirrhata]]'' does not produce sclerotia.<ref name=Bessette2007/>

==Habitat and distribution==
It is not known if ''C.&nbsp;tuberosa'' is strictly [[parasitism|parasitic]], and needs the [[host (biology)|host]] to be living, or whether it is [[saprobic]].<ref name="urlTom Volk's FTOM June 2004"/> Either way, the fruit bodies of the fungus are found growing solitarily or in dense clusters on the decomposing, often blackened remains of other mushrooms. Hosts include [[Agaricales|agarics]] (particularly ''[[Lactarius]]'' and ''[[Russula]]''),<ref name="urlKuo"/> [[bolete]]s, [[hydnum]]s, and [[polypore]]s.<ref name="urlHalling"/> In the [[Pacific Northwest]] region of the United States, ''[[Russula crassotunicata]]'' is a common and abundant species that has been definitively identified as a host of both ''C.&nbsp;tuberosa'' and ''[[Dendrocollybia racemosa]]''. The ''Russula'' fruit bodies are slow to decay, and are available nearly year-round as a substrate for the saprobes. Based on field observations, the authors suggest that ''C.&nbsp;tuberosa'' may produce fruit bodies on less decayed mushrooms, while ''D.&nbsp;racemosa'' produces them on much more heavily decayed mushrooms.<ref name=Machnicki2006/>

''Collybia tuberosa'' is found in Europe and North America,<ref name="urlRogers"/> and in most common in the summer and autumn, coinciding with the fruiting periods of other mushrooms.<ref name=Miller2006/> It has also been reported from Japan.<ref name=Ito1959/>

